  footnotes: []
english:
  title: The Weaver Woman's Lament
  author: Seo Geo-jeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Last night the frost wind shot through like arrows,
    On the loom the thread spools froze and cracked.
    By the loom the weaver woman joins the broken threads,
    Both her hands burst open, cold pierces deep into bone.
    She works the threads—click-clack, click-clack—the shuttle sings in winter,
    And sighs for herself, weaving cloth for another.
    The cloth done, she hurries down from the loom with scissors ready,
    Which debt presses harder—the official tax or the merchant's loan?
    Both claims upon her, neither can be refused,
    Yet how can she bear to go without skirt and stockings?
    Alas, already a farmer's wife,
    To go through the year in rags seems her appointed lot.
    She'll never learn the courtesan's trade,
    Dancing and singing for men, their coffers full of silk.
  footnotes:
    - The poem contrasts the weaver woman's harsh poverty with the silk-clad luxury of courtesans, suggesting how patriarchal feudal society valued women's labor differently based on their social position.
    - The specific mention of 'skirt and stockings' (치마·버선) represents basic necessities that even this laboring woman must do without, emphasizing the extremity of her deprivation.
